  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Memorial Inscription for the Addition of Posthumous Names at the Great Ancestral Temple, Second Shrine
  author: Choi Yu-chung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly reflect that sacrifices offered through a hundred generations know no end—this is the recompense for eminent virtue. When three years of mourning are completed, we must restore the solemn rites of grand ceremony. Thus we divine the auspicious day of early winter to raise the divine spirit to the Pure Temple. As we gather offerings according to the season, so do we perfect our sincerity; as we record virtue and proclaim merit, so do we hope it will endure for generations to come.

    I reverently consider that the Revered King Hye-jong, of transcendent wisdom, walked the path of his age. When the Divine Sage, our founder, first opened the kingdom, wicked and treacherous forces still wrought their cruelties. Through campaigns in all directions, he greatly rescued the people; through labors in a hundred pursuits, he ultimately built the great enterprise to completion. He then received the sacred mandate and brilliantly continued the royal succession. He marshaled heroes to guard the four quarters, so that martial glory extended ever farther; he unified the wheel and the written word to receive tribute from ten thousand nations, so that culture achieved perfect harmony. Thus did the towering virtue of one who followed the ancients become the model for our descendants.

    The Queen of Righteous Harmony, of the Lin clan, possessed a gentle and luminous nature and held a heart devoted to supporting the king. Her benevolence clothed the six palaces, worthy to match the noble consorts of ancient ages; her influence spread across the four seas, harmonizing with the kingly transformation of the lands of the South. Though the divine chariot has long departed, when I imagine her compassionate presence, she seems yet to abide.

    I, though unworthy and humble, have respectfully inherited the teachings entrusted to me. I perform this combined ancestral rite, symbolizing the auspicious gathering of his lifetime. I humbly present this charter bearing two characters of posthumous honor, that his great renown may endure for a thousand ages. Therefore, I reverently offer these gifts of oblation and present this memorial, adding the posthumous name of the Great King as [name], and the posthumous name of the Queen as [name]. I prostrate myself in hope that the enlightened divine spirit will graciously regard this sincere intention, accept this sacred charter, and preserve our descendants.
  footnotes:
    - Choi Yu-chung served as a high official during the Joseon dynasty. This memorial inscription was composed for a state ritual ceremony honoring a deceased king and queen with posthumous names.
    - The 'Pure Temple' (清廟) refers to the ancestral shrine where royal spirits were venerated.
    - Early winter (孟冬) was considered an auspicious time for major state ceremonies in East Asian tradition.
    - The 'two characters of posthumous honor' refers to the practice of bestowing two-character posthumous names (諡號) upon deceased rulers.
